  "output": "I read through the full codebase here — it's a small Go TUI (`main.go` + `tui.go`, ~430 lines, using Bubble Tea/Lipgloss to shell out to a Python crawler per provider). Two of your five categories don't apply: there's no React (no re-render concerns) and no database access (no N+1 queries) in this app. Here's what does apply, with concrete fixes.\n\n## 1. Quadratic re-render cost (real bug, not hypothetical)\n\n`tui.go:110-117` calls `refreshViewport()` on **every single incoming log line** for the highlighted provider:\n\n```go\nfunc (m *model) refreshViewport() {\n\tname := m.highlighted()\n\tif name == \"\" {\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tm.vp.SetContent(strings.Join(m.statuses[name].lines, \"\\n\")) // rejoins the WHOLE history\n\tm.vp.GotoBottom()\n}\n```\n\nFor a provider that emits `n` lines, this rejoins the entire accumulated slice on each of the `n` line arrivals → **O(n²)** total work for one crawl run. With `--limit 0` (unlimited) and a chatty crawler, this scales badly.\n\n**Fix** — maintain the joined string incrementally instead of rebuilding it from the slice:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tcontent strings.Builder // append-only, avoids O(n) rejoin per line\n}\n\n// in statusMsg handler:\nif st.content.Len() > 0 {\n\tst.content.WriteByte('\\n')\n}\nst.content.WriteString(msg.line)\nif m.highlighted() == msg.provider {\n\tm.vp.SetContent(st.content.String())\n\tm.vp.GotoBottom()\n}\n```\n\n## 2. Redundant recomputation every render tick\n\n`articlesSaved()` (`tui.go:365-373`) rescans a provider's *entire* line history from scratch, and `viewRunning()` calls it for **every provider, every render** — driven by the spinner's ~10Hz tick, not by new data:\n\n```go\ncount := articlesSaved(st.lines) // full rescan, 10x/sec, for all providers\n```\n\nThis is O(providers × total_lines) repeated continuously regardless of whether anything changed.\n\n**Fix** — track the count as a running counter updated only when a line arrives:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate        providerState\n\tlines        []string\n\tarticleCount int\n}\n\n// in statusMsg handler, replace the rescan with an incremental check:\nif strings.HasPrefix(msg.line, \"  - \") {\n\tst.articleCount++\n}\n```\nThen `viewRunning` just reads `st.articleCount` — no rescan needed, and `articlesSaved`/its call site can be deleted.\n\n## 3. Unbounded memory growth\n\n`providerStatus.lines` (`tui.go:37`) accumulates forever with no cap. Combined with `--limit 0`, a long crawl across 11 providers can hold arbitrarily large log history in memory for the process lifetime.\n\n**Fix**: cap retained history (e.g. keep the last 500 lines with a ring buffer), since the viewport only ever shows a scrollable window anyway:\n\n```go\nconst maxLines = 500\n\nst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\nif len(st.lines) > maxLines {\n\tst.lines = st.lines[len(st.lines)-maxLines:]\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Latent subprocess-hang risk (resource leak, not just perf)\n\n`main.go:83-86`:\n\n```go\nscanner := bufio.NewScanner(stdout)\nfor scanner.Scan() {\n\tonLine(scanner.Text())\n}\nreturn cmd.Wait()\n```\n\n`bufio.Scanner` defaults to a 64KB max line length (`bufio.MaxScanTokenSize`). If the Python crawler ever emits a single line over 64KB (a large JSON dump, a long traceback), `Scan()` returns `false` on `bufio.ErrTooLong` **silently** — `scanner.Err()` is never checked. The loop exits, but the child process is still writing to that same pipe; once its stdout buffer fills, the child blocks on write forever, and `cmd.Wait()` hangs — leaking a goroutine and a stuck subprocess until the user kills the TUI.\n\n**Fix**:\n```go\nscanner := bufio.NewScanner(stdout)\nscanner.Buffer(make([]byte, 64*1024), 1024*1024) // allow up to 1MB lines\nfor scanner.Scan() {\n\tonLine(scanner.Text())\n}\nif err := scanner.Err(); err != nil {\n\tonLine(\"scanner error: \" + err.Error())\n}\nreturn cmd.Wait()\n```\n\n## Not applicable here\n- **N+1 queries** / **caching opportunities**: no database or repeated-fetch layer exists in this app — it's a single `exec.CommandContext` per provider streaming stdout.\n- **React re-renders**: no React/JS in this app; the closest analog (Bubble Tea's render loop) is covered by #1/#2 above.\n\nPriority order if you want me to implement: #1 and #4 are the two that cause real bugs (quadratic slowdown, potential hangs); #2 and #3 are efficiency/hygiene. Want me to make these changes?\n",
